core-example/managing-some-thing.html.body:
Managing Some "Thing"
Suppose we have a component that renders some thing.  The component will extract thing from its props (properties) and render it.  We'll also add thing to the component's propTypes so that we know what type of thing the component expects.
// src/components/SomeThing.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';

const SomeThing = ({ thing }) => (

    Thing is currently: {thing}

);

SomeThing.propTypes = {
  thing: PropTypes.string.isRequired
};

export default SomeThing;

And then suppose we want another component to be able to set the current state of thing.  We'll use a function called setThing.  This is also extracted from the component's props, and we'll add an expected setThing function to its propTypes.  We'll render a button that prompts the user for the next thing when clicked.
// src/components/SomeThingSetter.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';

const SomeThingSetter = ({ setThing }) => (
   {
    const thing = window.prompt(`What should thing be?`);
    setThing(thing);
  }}>
    Click me to set thing.

);

SomeThingSetter.propTypes = {
  setThing: PropTypes.func.isRequired
};

export default SomeThingSetter;

Now we need to create a provider that can manage the state of thing.  For this example, all we need is a setThing action, and a thing reducer.
Let's break it down, step by step.
We'll create a value to represent the type of action taking place.  You can create any number of values to represent any number of action types.  These values will remain constant, which is why they are typically called constants.  For this example, we need just one constant.  Let's call it SET.
const SET = 'SET';

Now we need to create the setThing function used within the SomeThingSetter component above.  This function will accept a new thing as an input, and it will return an object containing the new thing along with the SET action type.
function setThing(thing) {
  return {
    type: SET,
    thing
  };
}

We can condense this function into a single line:
const setThing = (thing) => ({ type: SET, thing });

The object returned by the setThing function describes an action taking place.  A provider typically contains an actions object.  The actions object can contain any number of functions like this.
With that said, let's create an object called actions and put our setThing function in it.
const actions = {
  setThing: (thing) => ({ type: SET, thing })
};

Now we need to create a function that might return a new state for some thing.  This function should accept the current state and the action object as inputs.  It should always return either the current state of thing or a new state.  It will return a default thing if the current state is undefined.  And it will return the new thing if the action type matches our SET constant.
function thing(state, action) {
  if (action.type === SET) {
    return action.thing;
  } else if (typeof state === 'undefined') {
    return 'nothing';
  } else {
    return state;
  }
}

We can also condense this function into a single line:
const thing = (state = 'nothing', { type, thing }) => type === SET ? thing : state;

This function is a reducer.  A provider typically contains a reducers object to go with the actions object.  The reducers object can contain any number of functions like this.  Each reducer should be a pure function designed to return some state based on any action type.
With that said, let's create an object called reducers and put our thing function in it.
const reducers = {
  thing: (state = 'nothing', { type, thing }) => type === SET ? thing : state
};

These sets of actions and reducers become our provider module.  All that's left now is to export these actions and reducers within a single object.
// src/providers/thing.js

const SET = 'SET';

const actions = {
  setThing: (thing) => ({ type: SET, thing })
};

const reducers = {
  thing: (state = 'nothing', { type, thing }) => type === SET ? thing : state
};

export default { actions, reducers };

You may have noticed the following:

The SomeThing component's propTypes contains thing, which matches the name of our reducer function.

The SomeThingSetter component's propTypes contains setThing, which matches the name of our action function.


Matching propTypes is how react-redux-provide knows that it should create a shared provider instance for these components.  The SomeThingSetter component will automatically receive the setThing function.  And the SomeThing component will automatically receive the current state of thing.
Note that components don't receive the same exact actions and reducers functions.  They receive action creator functions and current states for matching keys.  The action creator functions will automatically dispatch (pass) the action object to each reducer.  All you should typically care about is the action objects and the states returned by each reducer.
Also note that an internal cache of reducer keys to components allows updates to be as efficient as possible.  The fastest code is code that never runs!
Next: More Than One "Thing"

core-example/more-than-one-thing.html.body:
More Than One "Thing"
Suppose you want to manage more than one thing.  All you do is add a key function to the provider definition.  This key function will receive each matched component instance.  It might look something like this:
const key = ({ props }) => `things/${props.thingId || ''}`;

We'll need to include this key function with the exported provider object:
// src/providers/thing.js

const SET = 'SET';

const key = ({ props }) => `things/${props.thingId || ''}`;

const actions = {
  setThing: (thing) => ({ type: SET, thing })
};

const reducers = {
  thing: (state = 'nothing', { type, thing }) => type === SET ? thing : state
};

export default { key, actions, reducers };

This allows us to have a different provider instance assigned to a component depending on the thingId property passed to it.
Now let's update our components' propTypes to expect the thingId prop.  We'll also render the thingId for the sake of obviousness:
// src/components/SomeThing.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';

const SomeThing = ({ thingId, thing }) => (

    Thing {thingId} is currently: {thing}

);

SomeThing.propTypes = {
  thingId: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
  thing: PropTypes.any.isRequired
};

export default SomeThing;

// src/components/SomeThingSetter.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';

const SomeThingSetter = ({ thingId, setThing }) => (
   {
    const thing = window.prompt(`What should thing ${thingId} be?`);
    setThing(thing);
  }}>
    Click me to set thing {thingId}.

);

SomeThingSetter.propTypes = {
  thingId: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
  setThing: PropTypes.func.isRequired
};

export default SomeThingSetter;

And then to put it all together as actual rendered components:
// src/components/Things.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';
import SomeThing from './SomeThing';
import SomeThingSetter from './SomeThingSetter';

const Things = () => (










);

export default Things;

This would ultimately produce the following HTML:


    Thing A is currently: nothing


    Click me to set thing A.



    Thing B is currently: nothing


    Click me to set thing B.



    Thing C is currently: nothing


    Click me to set thing C.



Clicking each button would of course allow us to update the current state of each thing.
Note that we can reuse these same components and/or propTypes (actions/reducers) any number of times.  The application will use the same provider instance for same values returned by the key function.
Next: Persisting State via Replication

core-example/persisting-state-via-replic.body:
Persisting State via Replication
Suppose you want to save and/or share the current state of each thing whenever it changes.  Replication allows you to do this in a way that keeps your application logic independent from your data sources.  It allows you to:

Instantly swap one data source for another.
Persist state locally.
Persist state to some backend via some API.
Share state in real-time via websockets or other means.
Do each of the above at the same time.

To enable replication for a provider, assign a replication object to it.  This object specifies how replicators should behave.  See redux-replicate for the full documentation on this object.
In our case, we have a single thing reducer.  With just one reducer, we can replicate the entire state, so we'll set reducerKeys to false within the replication object.  With many reducers, it could make more sense to set reducerKeys to true.  This would replicate each reducer's state upon individual changes rather than the entire state.  You can also use an array of reducerKeys to replicate specific states.
const replication = {
  reducerKeys: false
};

We'll need to include this with our thing provider as well.
// src/providers/thing.js

const SET = 'SET';

const key = ({ props }) => `things/${props.thingId || ''}`;

const actions = {
  setThing: (thing) => ({ type: SET, thing })
};

const reducers = {
  thing: (state = 'nothing', { type, thing }) => type === SET ? thing : state
};

const replication = {
  reducerKeys: false
};

export default { key, actions, reducers, replication };

In More Than One "Thing", we discussed the purpose of the provider's key function.  The value returned by this function is accessible via store.key.  Replicators can use the store and its key to save/share actions and state changes.  Replicators are like providers in that they're a composition of functions.  Replicators are typically designed to work with any provider.
Suppose you want to get the initial state of each thing from an API.  A replicator's getInitialState function will receive the store along with a setState function and a setError function.  Let's use this to create our own getInitialState function which will fetch the current state from our API.
const getInitialState = ({ store, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

For example, if thingId is "A", then the store.key would be things/A and this getInitialState function would fetch the state of thing "A" from the API via the URL /api/things/A.  It then attempts to convert the response to JSON which becomes the initial state via setState.  If there's an error, it's caught by setError instead.
Replicating state changes to the API works similarly.  The onStateChange function receives the same properties as getInitialState plus some others (see full API reference).  For our particular case, we need nextState and create.  The create property will be a function when creating a new provider instance.  This is useful when the client relies on the server's state.  For example, the client can't create and cache the correct store.key without the server returning a new thingId.  The easiest way to achieve this is by calling the thunk API's createInstance function.
const onStateChange = ({ store, nextState, create, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`, {
    method: create ? 'POST' : 'PATCH',
    body: JSON.stringify(nextState),
    headers: {
      'Accept': 'application/json',
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    }
  })
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(create || setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

If we're creating a new thing instance, the store.key will be things/, which means we'll POST the nextState to /api/things/.  We expect the server to return JSON containing any missing state - e.g., thingId - which the create function handles.
If we're not creating a new thing instance, we're just replicating the new state to the API.  Suppose the state of thing "A" has changed.  This onStateChange function would send the nextState to the server as a PATCH request to the URL /api/things/A.
Putting these two functions together will form our replicator:
// src/replicators/backend.js

const getInitialState = ({ store, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

const onStateChange = ({ store, nextState, create, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`, {
    method: create ? 'POST' : 'PATCH',
    body: JSON.stringify(nextState),
    headers: {
      'Accept': 'application/json',
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    }
  })
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(create || setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

export default { getInitialState, onStateChange };

Next: Querying Replicated States

core-example/querying-replicated-states..body:
Querying Replicated States
You may not care about this topic until later on, but it's good to know about sooner rather than later.
Most data sources allow you to query for stored data.  In our case, this data represents the states of any number of Redux stores, created by our providers.
Suppose we want to find each thing with a current state of "apple" within this data source.  To enable this within our React components, we first need to add a handleQuery function to our replicator.  This function works like getInitialState, but instead of a setState function, it receives a setResult function.  It also receives a query object and an options object.  The store passed to it is typically a "base" store for any matching reducers but its key would be without, for example, a thingId.
const toParams = obj => Object.keys(obj)
  .map(key => `${encodeURIComponent(key)}=${encodeURIComponent(obj[key])}`)
  .join('&');

const handleQuery = ({ store, query, setResult, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}?${toParams(query)}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(setResult)
    .catch(setError)
);

We will need to export the handleQuery function along with getInitialState and onStateChange:
// src/replicators/backend.js

const getInitialState = ({ store, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

const onStateChange = ({ store, nextState, create, setState, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}`, {
    method: create ? 'POST' : 'PATCH',
    body: JSON.stringify(nextState),
    headers: {
      'Accept': 'application/json',
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    }
  })
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(create || setState)
    .catch(setError)
);

const toParams = obj => Object.keys(obj)
  .map(key => `${encodeURIComponent(key)}=${encodeURIComponent(obj[key])}`)
  .join('&');

const handleQuery = ({ store, query, setResult, setError }) => (
  fetch(`/api/${store.key}?${toParams(query)}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(setResult)
    .catch(setError)
);

export default { getInitialState, onStateChange, handleQuery };

Now querying for states from within our React components is just a matter of specifying a query prop type and a result prop type:
// src/components/Apples.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';
import SomeThing from './SomeThing';

const Apples = ({ result }) => {
  if (result === null) {
    return (

        Finding apples...

    );
  } else if (!result || !result.length) {
    return (

        No apples found!

    );
  } else {
    return (

        {result.map(thingState => (

        ))}

    );
  }
};

Apples.propTypes = {
  query: PropTypes.any,
  result: PropTypes.any
};

Apples.defaultProps = {
  query: { thing: 'apple' }
};

export default Apples;

The query prop may also be a function.  Suppose we want a generic ThingFinder component.  Everything remains the same except for the query prop, which becomes a function of the component itself.
// src/components/ThingFinder.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';
import SomeThing from './SomeThing';

const ThingFinder = ({ thing, result }) => {
  if (result === null) {
    return (

        Finding {thing}...

    );
  } else if (!result || !result.length) {
    return (

        No {thing} found!

    );
  } else {
    return (

        {result.map(thingState => (

        ))}

    );
  }
};

ThingFinder.propTypes = {
  thing: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
  query: PropTypes.any,
  result: PropTypes.any
};

ThingFinder.defaultProps = {
  query: ({ props }) => ({ thing: props.thing })
};

export default ThingFinder;

We could then use this generic ThingFinder component to find any thing:
// src/components/Apples.js

import React, { PropTypes } from 'react';
import ThingFinder from './ThingFinder';

const Apples = () => (

);

export default Apples;

Next: Tying Everything Together

core-example/tying-everything-together.h.body:
Tying Everything Together
As you may have noticed, the components don't depend on (import) the providers.  The providers don't depend on the components or the replicators.  And the replicators don't depend on the components or the providers.  Each piece of the application is as decoupled as possible.
With each piece so separate from one another, how do we put it all together?
When mounting the app, we'll import the replicator(s), the providers, and the top level component.  We'll use react-redux-provide's pushReplicator utility function.  We'll also use its install method, which automatically enables providers for all components.  Note that the install method may not be necessary in the future when React's context has matured.
import 'react-redux-provide/lib/install';
import React from 'react';
import { render } from 'react-dom';
import { pushReplicator } from 'react-redux-provide';
import backend from './replicators/backend';
import * as providers from './providers/index';
import App from './components/App';

Notice that we're importing the providers from an index module.  It's good practice to use an index module which exports each provider within the app.  We have just one provider in this particular example, but most applications will use more than a handful.
// src/providers/index.js

export thing from './thing';

Last but not least, all we need to do now is push our backend replicator onto our providers and pass our providers as a property to our top-level component.
// src/renderApp.js

import 'react-redux-provide/lib/install';
import React from 'react';
import { render } from 'react-dom';
import { pushReplicator } from 'react-redux-provide';
import backend from './replicators/backend';
import * as providers from './providers/index';
import App from './components/App';

pushReplicator(providers, backend);

function renderApp(props, element = document.getElementById('root')) {
  return render(, element);
}

renderApp({ providers });

export default renderApp;

That's it!  The concepts covered throughout this example are what you'll use the most.
If you're ready for more advanced use-cases, checkout the Extended Documentation.

extended-documentation/what-is-a-provide.body:
actions
Object containing Redux actions.
const PUSH_ITEM = 'PUSH_ITEM';

const actions = {
  pushItem(item) {
    return { type: PUSH_ITEM, item };
  }
};

Note: When providing each action creator to React components, the result of the action creator is automatically wrapped with providerInstance.store.dispatch, so with the above example, when you call this.props.pushItem(item), you're ultimately calling providerInstance.store.dispatch(actions.pushItem(item)).
Next: reducers

reducers
Object containing Redux reducers.
const reducers = {
  list(state = [], action) {
    switch (action.type) {
      case PUSH_ITEM:
        return state.concat(action.item);

      default:
        return state;
    }
  }
};

Note: Components will only be updated whenever a relevant reducer returns a new state - i.e., when state !== nextState.
Next: merge

merge
Optional object used for deriving props which depend on the state of the store, possibly merged with the component's props and/or context.  For example, suppose one of the reducers returns an array, and some component only wants some item at a specific index.
const merge = {
  item: {
    keys: ['list'], // run `get` function only when list changes
    get(state, props, context) {
      // this is run only for components with an item propType
      // and components will be updated only when the item has changed
      const { list } = state;
      const { itemIndex } = props;

      return list[itemIndex] || null;
    }
  }
};

Next: middleware

middleware
Optional Redux middleware specific to your provider.  This can be either a single middleware or an array of middlewares.
import createLogger from 'redux-logger';

const middleware = createLogger();
// or const middleware = [ createLogger() ];

Note: Every provider is given its own custom thunk middleware.  It works the same as redux-thunk but always includes a special third providerApi argument.  See the thunk API section.
Next: enhancer

enhancer
Optional Redux store enhancer specific to your provider.  This can be either a single enhancer or an array of enhancers.
// from `provide-theme`
// ensures current theme is always initialized
// mainly for when store.setState or store.setKey is called

const enhancer = next => (reducer, initialState, enhancer) => {
  const store = next(reducer, initialState, enhancer);
  let currentThemeName = null;

  function setTheme(state, init) {
    const { dispatch, getState } = store;
    const { themes, themesFiles, themeName } = state;
    const theme = themes && themes[themeName] || init && state.theme;
    const themeFiles = themesFiles && themesFiles[themeName];
    let initAction = null;

    currentThemeName = themeName;

    if (theme || themeFiles) {
      initAction = theme && actions.initTheme(themeName, themeFiles, theme);

      if (initAction && (!canUseDOM || initAction.link && initAction.script)) {
        store.dispatch(initAction);
      } else if (canUseDOM) {
        actions.loadTheme(themeName, themeFiles, theme)(dispatch, getState);
      } else {
        store.dispatch(actions.loadTheme(themeName, themeFiles, theme));
      }
    }
  }

  setTheme(initialState || {}, true);

  store.subscribe(() => {
    const nextState = store.getState();

    if (nextState.themeName !== currentThemeName) {
      setTheme(nextState);
    }
  });

  return store;
};

Next: Initialization

state
Optional object used for overriding the store's initial state.  This is typically used only when the initial state can be derived from the current request and/or session, as the default initial state should come from the reducers themselves.  It works best to copy and extend providers using the spread operator.
renderApp({
  providers: {
    ...providers,
    theme: {
      ...providers.theme,
      state: themeState
    }
  }
});

Next: onInstantiated

onInstantiated
Optional function or array of functions to be called immediately after the provider has been instantiated and before its optional replicators have initialized.  The provider instance will be passed to the function(s).
function onInstantiated(providerInstance) {
  console.log(providerInstance);
}

Next: onReady

onReady
Optional function or array of functions to be called immediately after the provider and its optional replicators have initialized.  The provider instance will be passed to the function(s).
function onReady(providerInstance) {
  console.log(providerInstance);
}

Additionally: During the very first tick of the app only on the client, the root provider component will look for a window.clientStates object and convert it to provider instances which are cached within the current context.  Each state is removed from the window.clientStates object as a result.  If you're using the official page provider, you won't ever need to worry about this.  See provide-page/src/defaultRenderDocumentToString.js for an example where the client states are extracted from the server's provider instances' stores, stringified (using JSON.stringify) and sent to the client for the initial render.
Next: Replication

replication
Optional object or array of objects.  Uses redux-replicate (a Redux store enhancer) under the hood.  Each object should contain keys that match the arguments expected by redux-replicate - i.e., { key, reducerKeys, replicator, queryable (optional), clientState (optional) }.  The key will default to the provider instance's providerKey.
Example where some user provider instance's states are replicated to flat files whenever they change:
import fs from 'redux-replicate-fs';

const replication = {
  // only these reducers are watched/replicated
  reducerKeys: [
    'userId',
    'userName',
    'userPasswordHash'
  ],
  // and we want to be able to retrieve user instances by `userName`
  queryable: [
    'userName'
  ],
  // and here we'll use node's file system API to store states in flat files
  replicator: fs
};

See redux-replicate for the full documentation which can be used within the replication object.  Also see redux-replicate-fs for an example replicator implementation that gets the initial state, stores states upon changes, and handles queries.
Next: baseQuery

baseQuery
Optional object that can be used as the base of each query.  For example, if you know you almost always want to search for accounts that have not been deactivated, you would set the baseQuery within your replication object as follows:
const replication = {
  reducerKeys: [
    'accountName',
    'accountDeactivated'
  ],
  queryable: true,
  baseQuery: {
    accountDeactivated: false
  }
};

Next: baseQueryOptions

baseQueryOptions
Optional object that can be used as the base of each query's options.  For example, if you want to limit the query results to some number by default:
const replication = {
  reducerKeys: [
    'userId',
    'userName',
    'userPasswordHash'
  ],
  queryable: [
    'userName',
    'userDeleted'
  ],
  baseQuery: {
    userDeleted: false
  },
  baseQueryOptions: {
    limit: 100
  }
};

Next: clientStateKeys

subscribeTo
Optional object which will automatically subscribe to any matching providers by key.  Each value within the object should be a function that accepts the subscribed to provider instance as the first argument and the subscribing instance as the second argument.
For example, suppose you have a static theme provider instance and you want its state to depend on the currently logged in user (to represent their selected theme).  And suppose you're using the page provider to contain the current userId within its requestSession state object.  You could set the theme provider to subscribe to the page provider such that it updates the theme store's key like this:
import theme from 'provide-theme';

function getThemeKey(pageState) {
  const { userId } = pageState.requestSession;

  return userId ? `theme&userId=${userId}` : null;
}

// disable replication by default
theme.replication.key = null;

theme.subscribeTo = {
  page({ store: pageStore }, { store: themeStore }) {
    // stores have a `setKey` method that allows you to change their key,
    // which will reinitialize the store (i.e., state) based on the new key;
    // only the replication key is changed, not the key used for identifying
    // the provide instance
    if (themeStore.setKey) {
      const themeKey = getThemeKey(pageStore.getState());

      if (themeKey !== themeStore.key) {
        themeStore.setKey(themeKey);
      }
    }
  }
};

export default theme;

Next: subscribers

subscribers
Optional object which will automatically subscribe any matching providers by key.  Each value within the object should be a function that accepts the subscribed to provider instance as the first argument and the subscribing instance as the second argument.
Works exactly like subscribeTo but in the opposite direction.  The following is equivalent to the subscribeTo example above (but don't do both because that would be silly):
import page from 'provide-page';

function getThemeKey(pageState) {
  const { userId } = pageState.requestSession;

  return userId ? `theme&userId=${userId}` : null;
}

page.subscribers = {
  theme({ store: pageStore }, { store: themeStore }) {
    if (themeStore.setKey) {
      const themeKey = getThemeKey(pageStore.getState());

      if (themeKey !== themeStore.key) {
        themeStore.setKey(themeKey);
      }
    }
  }
};

export default page;

Next: wait

clear
Optional function that is called whenever a provider instance finishes doing something asynchronously.  The function will be called with true as the first argument if the provider instance's store's state has changed.
The wait and clear functions are useful for things like server rendering, where you need to wait for asynchronous operations to complete before continuing.
Quick example:
import { pushWait, pushClear } from 'react-redux-provide';
import * as providers from './providers/index';

let rerender = false;
let waitCount = 0;

function wait() {
  waitCount++;

  console.log(`Waiting for async operation (${waitCount}) to finish...`);
}

function clear(stateChanged) {
  if (stateChanged) {
    rerender = true;
  }

  console.log(`Async operation (${waitCount}) done!`);

  if (stateChanged) {
    console.log(`The state changed during this operation.`);
  } else {
    console.log(`The state did not change during this operation.`);
  }

  if (--waitCount === 0) {
    respondOrRerender();
  }
}

pushWait(providers, wait);
pushClear(providers, clear);

// etc.

See provide-page/src/createMiddleware.js for a full example.
Next: isGlobal

Thunk API
All providers are given a special thunk middleware which includes a providerApi object as a third argument to the action's returned function.  The providerApi contains a handful of useful functions for getting provider instance(s), setting provider states, dispatching actions, and finding data and/or getting instantiated providers based on that data.  Any sorting/grouping is left entirely up to the replicator and the options passed to its handleQuery function.
For example, suppose you want unique user names.
You would start by setting the user provider's replication property such that the userName state is queryable:
const replication = {
  // only these reducers are watched/replicated
  reducerKeys: [
    'userId',
    'userName',
    'userPasswordHash'
  ],
  // and we want to be able to retrieve user instances by `userName`
  queryable: [
    'userName'
  ],
  // and here we'll use node's file system API to store states in flat files
  replicator: fs
};

And then the createUser action would look like this:
const actions = {
  createUser(state, genUserId, onSuccess) {
    const { userName, userPassword } = state;

    if (!userName) {
      return actions.setUserError('Enter a name!');
    }

    if (!userPassword) {
      return actions.setUserError('Enter a password!');
    }

    return (dispatch, getState, { createInstance, find }) => {
      // here we need to ensure the user name is not already in use
      find({ query: { userName }, options: { select: 'userId' } }, results => {
        if (results && results.length) {
          dispatch(actions.setUserError('User exists!'));
          return;
        }

        const defaultState = getState();
        const {
          hasher = defaultState.hasher,
          saltRounds = defaultState.saltRounds
        } = state;

        hasher.hash(userPassword, saltRounds, (error, userPasswordHash) => {
          if (!userPasswordHash) {
            dispatch(actions.setUserError('Error hashing password!'));
            return;
          }

          // here we instantiate the user instance within the current context
          // using the proper key - i.e., `userId=state.userId`
          // and then the CREATE_USER action sets the proper userId, userName, etc.
          // which is then replicated to your database of choice
          state.userId = genUserId();

          createInstance(state, userInstance => {
            userInstance.store.dispatch({
              ...state,
              userPasswordHash,
              type: CREATE_USER
            });

            dispatch({
              ...state,
              type: CREATED_USER
            });

            if (onSuccess) {
              onSuccess(state.userId);
            }
          });
        });
      });
    };
  }
};

Next: getInstance

